SUMMARY: Art Exhibition | Designing Nature: Elements of Harmony
DESCRIPTION:Japanese gardens are living expressions of harmony—where natu
 re is shaped by human hands and guided by the heart. Designing Nature\, a
  new exhibition at Portland Japanese Garden\, invites you to explore the 
 people\, traditions\, and philosophies behind this timeless art form—reve
 aling the depth\, intention\, and beauty that define Japanese garden desi
 gn. Whether you’re seeking a quiet moment of reflection\, a deeper connec
 tion to the natural world\, or a spark of creative inspiration\, the Gard
 en welcomes all who enter.\n\nThis exhibition represents a collaboration 
 between Portland Japanese Garden’s two curators:\n\n  * Aki Nakanishi\, D
 irector of Japan Institute and Arlene Schnitzer Curator of Culture\, Art\
 , and Education\n  * Hugo Torii\, Garden Curator and Director of the Japa
 nese Garden Training Center\n\nPavilion Gallery\nAs you enter the Pavilio
 n Gallery you’ll step back in time through a visual journey of the histor
 y\, techniques\, and ideas that have shaped Japanese garden design from a
 ntiquity through the present day. A closer look at the design of the dive
 rse garden styles of Portland Japanese Garden will be explored through sc
 ale miniatures constructed by architectural model maker\, Aimee Eng. Lear
 n how the three basic garden elements of water\, plant\, and stone have i
 nspired a tapestry of creativity across the ages. Featuring a large-scale
  waterfall painting of contemporary nihonga painter Hiroshi Senju\, a bam
 boo sculpture from Chikuunsai Tanabe IV and acclaimed artist Honda Syoryu
 \, and a selection of suiseki\, landscape scene stones\, from the collect
 ion of Andrew and Jeffrey Robson.\n\nCalvin and Mayho Tanabe Gallery\nThe
  exhibition continues in the Jordan Schnitzer Japanese Arts Learning Cent
 er. Travel to Japan through a curated selection of photographs from four 
 prominent gardens based in Japan: Kairaku-en\, Kenroku-en\, Koraku-en\, a
 nd Ritsurin in the Calvin and Mayho Tanabe Gallery. Members and visitors 
 are invited to learn more about the rich history and traditions of garden
  design from a selection of books in our Vollum Library\, located on the 
 Learning Center’s second floor.\n\nThe Living Room Gallery\nPortland Japa
 nese Garden is a love letter from the past to the future\, embodying the 
 efforts and care of many over the years. Photographer Stu Levy has been a
  neighbor of the Garden for over 50 years and has captured its timeless b
 eauty through his black and white images of scenes that echo across the y
 ears. From flowing water to mist in the trees\, these images evoke medita
 tive moments through a unique perspective.\n\nThe Cathy Rudd Cultural Cor
 ner\nFrom October 18 through November 17\, Cross Currents will be on disp
 lay in the Cathy Rudd Cultural Corner. This graceful installation inspire
 s awe at the artistry and malleability of bamboo and its role in Japanese
  gardens and cultural traditions. Crafted by Portland-based bamboo artist
  Anne Crumpacker\, Cross Currents was donated to Portland Japanese Garden
  by Anne and Mark Edlen in 2024. The artwork showcases Crumpacker’s innov
 ative crosscut bamboo technique through this installation of interwoven p
 anels that evoke a meditative landscape.
CATEGORIES:art,exhibition,garden
